[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hello creators and creative friends. Welcome to the channel. A month ago, I showed you a workflow that lets you change the camera angle and pose of character or subject. That one used the Qwen image edit model. Today, I\'ve got a similar workflow for you. It does the'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same thing, but this time it\'s based on the Flex to Depth model. This workflow was built on RunDiffusion, a comfy cloud platform. It comes with most models and custom nodes pre-installed. Check the video'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'description if you want to learn more. Let\'s take a look at the output first. On the left, you have the original portrait. On the right, you see the result from this workflow. Notice how the camera angle and the pose have'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'changed, but the identity stays the same. There are two main node groups here. The first group is similar to the one we used with Qwen image edit. I\'ll keep this explanation brief, but I\'ll leave a link to the previous workflow if you'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want more details. This group is in charge of generating a prompt that includes both camera angle and pose information. The camera angle comes from this Qwen multi-angle camera nodes. Don\'t be fooled by the name. It works'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with any model, not just Qwen. You can preview the prompt here. The asking S in angle brackets is the trigger for the Laura in the next group. The words after that describe the camera'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'angle. The node below generates a pose prompt based on the uploaded portrait, but you can also write your own prompt here. You can switch between the two using the'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'switch node. At the end of this group, a node combines the camera angle and pose into one final prompt, which gets sent to the next group. The core of this group is a multi-angle'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Laura. Give it some love on Hugging Face if you like. This Laura can handle 72 unique camera positions. It\'s trained on Flex to Depth, which is why we\'re using that model here. I\'m not sure why Flex'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to Klein wasn\'t used for training that Lara. Maybe it\'s easier to mess up the anatomy with that one. The FP version of Flagstone app is huge, 35.5 gigabytes. I\'m using a GGF version, which is about'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '20 gigabytes. If your VRAM is limited, smaller versions also work. I\'ve also added a turbo Laura. Without it, it need at least 20 sampling steps. Right now, the output keeps the same'

[02:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aspect ratio as the original portrait, but if you want a different ratio, just customize the width and height here and switch the building to false. Let\'s rerun it. Now you can see the new aspect ratio,'

[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and that\'s it for today. If you want to download this workflow, join our community and support the channel. Thanks for watching.'
